{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_019efd2ZtLBDtJaqBzsPwgpj","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I understand the full picture:\n\n1. The StatefulSet uses an **init container** (`copy-cookie`) that:\n   - Mounts the secret `rabbitmq-cookie-perpod` at `/cookie-src`\n   - Copies `/cookie-src/${POD_NAME}` to `/cookie-dst/.erlang.cookie` (an emptyDir volume)\n   - Sets permissions on the cookie\n   \n2. The main container mounts the emptyDir at `/var/lib/rabbitmq/.erlang.cookie`\n\n3. The secret has `rabbitmq-0` and `rabbitmq-1` with `supersecretcookie` but `rabbitmq-2` with `driftedcookie`.\n   \nSince the cookie lives on an emptyDir that gets repopulated from the secret on every restart, the fix is straightforward: update the secret to give `rabbitmq-2` the same cookie value as the others, then delete the pod to trigger a restart and let the init container copy the corrected cookie. After that, the peer discovery mechanism should automatically reintegrate it into the cluster, though there might be additional complications depending on the cluster's current state.\n\nActually, wait — there's a deeper issue here. Even after fixing the cookie and restarting, `rabbitmq-2` still has its own mnesia data directory on the PVC with a different cluster identity baked in. RabbitMQ will boot using that existing data rather than joining fresh, so I need to reset the mnesia directory first. The proper sequence is to fix the cookie, restart the pod, then use `rabbitmqctl` commands to stop the app, reset the node state, and explicitly join it back to the cluster. The `reset` command clears the mnesia database so the node forgets its previous cluster membership, which is safe here since rabbitmq-2 has no unique data. I'm decoding the cookie values from the secret to confirm they're different — one is \"supersecretcookie\" and the other is \"driftedcookie\" — then I'll patch the secret and delete the pod to trigger the init container with the correct cookie. Looking at the logs more carefully, rabbitmq-2 is starting fresh as a standalone node rather than failing to join due to a cookie mismatch. I need to patch the secret with the correct base64-encoded cookie value and then rejoin the cluster using the proper headless service DNS name.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":3046,"cache_read_input_tokens":39314,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":3046},"output_tokens":25,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"f6c3cc50-0ae1-4483-aa74-5c8fe22ae47b","uuid":"9baf11bd-04f8-41a2-961e-e9c7c7e83c25","request_id":"req_011Cbzr7y3nE7vK7f7gmMXzn"}
{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_019efd2ZtLBDtJaqBzsPwgpj","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"The problem is clear: the secret `rabbitmq-cookie-perpod` has `rabbitmq-2` with cookie `driftedcookie` while nodes 0 and 1 have `supersecretcookie`. The init container copies this bad cookie into the pod, so rabbitmq-2 can't join the cluster.\n\n**Fix plan:**\n1. Patch the secret to give rabbitmq-2 the correct cookie\n2. Delete the rabbitmq-2 pod (init container re-runs with corrected cookie)\n3. Once it's up (still solo), exec in to `reset` + `join_cluster`\n\nLet me verify the base64 values first:"}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":3046,"cache_read_input_tokens":39314,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":3046},"output_tokens":25,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"f6c3cc50-0ae1-4483-aa74-5c8fe22ae47b","uuid":"52090996-5367-4bd8-b471-f9d36ff74429","request_id":"req_011Cbzr7y3nE7vK7f7gmMXzn"}
